  Q1=sp[i].quantile(0.25)
  Q3=sp[i].quantile(0.75)
  IQR=Q3-Q1
  lower=Q1-1.5*IQR
  upper=Q3+1.5*IQR
  outliers=sp[(sp[i]<lower) | (sp[i]>upper)]
  print(f"{i} has {len(outliers)} outliers")

INSIGHT FOR STUDENT PERFORMANCE IN EXAMS

Key InsightsStudent Performance in Exams

1. Parental Education Level Influences Scores Students whose parents have a higher level of education (Bachelors/Masters degree) tend to score significantly higher across math, reading, and writing.

Lower parental education levels (e.g., high school or below) correlate with lower average student scores.

2. Test Preparation Course Works Students who completed the test preparation course consistently perform better in all three subjects.

The average improvement is especially noticeable in writing and reading scores.

3. Gender-Based Performance Trends Male students generally perform better in math, while female students tend to outperform in reading and writing.

This suggests potential gender-specific strengths and learning preferences.

4. Lunch Type Has a Noticeable Impact Students receiving standard lunch perform better than those with free/reduced lunch, indicating a possible link between nutrition and academic performance.

5. Subject-wise Correlation There is a strong correlation between reading and writing scores students who perform well in one tend to do well in the other.

Math has a moderate but still significant correlation with the other subjects.

6. Overall Performance Distribution Most students score between 6080 marks, but very few reach 100.

A small percentage fall below 50, indicating a need for targeted academic support.

7. Students at Risk Students who did not complete the prep course, have low parental education, and receive free/reduced lunch are at higher risk of underperformance.
